@audience plop-reviewers
@tone invitational
@allow-new-claims true
@order 1

! conclusion:
  Set expectations that the paper distills conceptual lessons from simulated
  workshops rather than unveiling a production-ready system, while signalling the
  three analytic lenses that anchor the rest of the text.

  + CONTEXT:
    We ran narrative-rich GPT workshops to probe how PLACARD-era pattern methods
    behave when orchestrated by virtual facilitators and fictional agents.

  + IF:
    Readers know that these simulations served as thinking tools, not
    deliverables, and that we will repeatedly view them through Project Action
    Reviews, Causal Layered Analysis, and a simple “next steps” clause that keeps
    patterns curious.

  + HOWEVER:
    Without a clear preface, reviewers might expect implementation detail or
    empirical validation we cannot provide, or assume the analytic lenses are new
    inventions rather than familiar practices applied in concert.

  + THEN:
    Open with a candid statement: the prototypes shaped our understanding, the
    paper gathers the resulting insights, and the trio of lenses will be used as
    interpretive tools throughout.

  + BECAUSE:
    Front-loading intent keeps the scope legible, prevents reviewers from
    chasing missing code, and frames each later section as part of a reflective
    synthesis instead of a systems pitch.

  + NEXT STEPS:
    Draft the prefatory paragraphs using plain, fairy-tale language that names
    the simulations, introduces the lenses, and emphasizes that what follows is a
    distillation meant for designers and educators alike.


;;; /home/joe/code/patterns-685450173d4ea701e814d930/outline/introduction.flexiarg

@arg popiii/introduction
@title Introduction: What a Pattern Wants
@audience plop-reviewers
@tone lucid
@allow-new-claims true
@order 2

! conclusion:
  Introduce design patterns as living predictive cells that sense context,
  surface tensions, act, and keep a “next steps” clause to gather new evidence,
  while highlighting PAR and CLA as complementary bundles for coordinating them.

  + CONTEXT:
    Readers arrive with varied notions of “pattern”—some think of catalogues,
    others of reusable code—and need a story that links the PLACARD lineage to
    present-day questions about agency and pedagogy.

  + IF:
    We render a pattern as a Jeff Hawkins-style neuron—firing when context and
    tension align, dampening noise, and triggering action—and explain that the
    added “next steps” clause keeps it collecting evidence over time.

  + HOWEVER:
    Too much machinery (predictive processing jargon, PAR/CLA mechanics) could
    swamp the introduction, obscuring the reader-friendly story before it begins.

  + THEN:
    Use simple metaphors: PAR is the with-the-grain bundle that gathers agents in
    a shared moment; CLA is the across-the-grain bundle that rewrites the story;
    together, they keep a collection of patterns healthy as they learn.

  + BECAUSE:
    This framing shows why patterns matter beyond documentation—they are active
    participants in inquiry—and primes readers for the rest of the paper without
    demanding technical background.

  + NEXT STEPS:
    Draft two concise introduction paragraphs that (1) define patterns via the
    neuron metaphor plus the curiosity clause, and (2) preview PAR and CLA as the
    lenses we use to understand how patterns travel through workshops and futures.


