@arg popiii/pattern-competent-agents
@title Toward Pattern-Competent Agents
@audience plop-reviewers
@tone speculative-grounded
@allow-new-claims true
@order 4

! conclusion:
  Translate workshop insights into three design requirements—recognition,
  flexiformal expression, and reflection loops—showing why they matter for any
  future transition from simulated to embodied agents.

  + CONTEXT:
    Readers are curious about what happens if patterns stop being purely human
    artefacts and start living inside software or mixed collectives.

  + IF:
    We present each requirement as a “threshold” that the simulations illuminated
    (e.g., agents need to notice when a pattern should fire, interpret its clauses
    legibly, and keep it evolving via PAR/CLA-like loops).

  + HOWEVER:
    Getting lost in prototype detail would derail the reflective tone and invite
    requests for benchmarks.

  + THEN:
    Use narrative vignettes drawn from the simulations: describe what went right
    or wrong in a virtual breakout, extrapolate the requirement, and sketch what a
    cautious real-world implementation would have to respect.

  + BECAUSE:
    This lets us talk about why the simulated→real transition matters—accountable
    memory, transparent roles, living evidence—without overclaiming progress.

  + NEXT STEPS:
    Draft three subsections (Recognition, Flexiformality, Reflection) each with a
    vignette, a requirement statement, and a note about implications for future
    agent design.


